# Kubernetes & ArgoCD Conventions

## Manifest Structure

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  AppCR["k8s/apps/argocd/applications/svc-app.yaml"] -->|watches| SvcDir["k8s/apps/svc/"]
  SvcDir --> Kustomization["kustomization.yaml"]
  Kustomization --> Resources["namespace / pvc / secret / configmap / deployment / service"]
```

## ArgoCD Application CRs

When creating or editing Application CRs, follow the rules in `k8s/apps/argocd/README.md`:

- Assign to the correct AppProject: `secrets` (secret infra), `data` (databases), `apps` (user-facing services). Never use `default`.
- Include all four `app.kubernetes.io/*` labels: `name` (matches metadata.name), `part-of` (always `homelab`), `component` (functional role), `managed-by` (always `argocd`).
- If the destination namespace is not in the project's `destinations`, add it to `k8s/apps/argocd/projects/<project>.yaml`.
- If deploying cluster-scoped resources (CRDs, ClusterRoles), add them to the project's `clusterResourceWhitelist`.
- List the Application file in `k8s/apps/argocd/kustomization.yaml`.

## Sync Waves

```mermaid
flowchart LR
  W1["Wave -1: AppProjects"] --> W0["Wave 0: external-secrets (CRDs)"]
  W0 --> W1a["Wave 1: external-secrets-config (ClusterSecretStore)"]
  W1a --> WD["Default: all other apps"]
```

## Secrets

Never put secret values in manifests. Use an `ExternalSecret` resource that references keys from Infisical. Use the `/secret-management` skill for the pattern.

## Kustomize

- Every service directory must have a `kustomization.yaml` with a `resources:` list.
- Use `namespace.yaml` only when the service owns its namespace creation.
- Prefer `CreateNamespace=true` in the ArgoCD Application syncOptions unless another app already creates the namespace.

## Helm Value Verification (mandatory)

Before modifying any `helm.valuesObject` in an ArgoCD Application CR, **always** verify the key path exists in the chart. Helm charts silently ignore unknown keys — the setting appears configured but has no effect on rendered manifests.

```bash
# Verify the key exists
helm show values <repo>/<chart> --version <version> | grep -A5 "<key>"

# Confirm the value renders into the output
helm template <release> <repo>/<chart> --version <version> \
  --set <key>=<value> | grep -A10 "<expected-output>"
```

If the key doesn't appear in `helm show values`, do NOT add it to `valuesObject`. Check the chart's README or source templates for the correct path.

## Security Context Changes

When adding `securityContext` to a deployment:

- Verify the container image supports running as non-root (some images use init systems like s6-overlay that require root at startup)
- Check if the upstream Helm chart already sets a default `securityContext` (avoid redundant or conflicting settings)
- Test `fsGroup` compatibility with the volume provisioner (OrbStack local-path uses GID 0)
- For Helm-managed apps, confirm the `securityContext` key path is templated into the Deployment spec

## Rollback

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  Bad[Bad commit on main] --> Revert["git revert + git push main"]
  Revert --> Sync{ArgoCD syncs?}
  Sync -->|yes| Healthy[Cluster restored]
  Sync -->|stuck| Cancel["kubectl patch: remove /operation"]
  Cancel --> Refresh["kubectl patch: hard refresh annotation"]
  Refresh --> Healthy
```

Never rely solely on `kubectl rollout undo` — ArgoCD will overwrite it. Use the `/incident-response` skill for the full procedure.

## Documentation

Every `k8s/apps/<service>/` directory **must** have a `README.md`. This README is the single source of truth for that service's documentation — `docs/<service>.md` is just a thin `include-markdown` wrapper. See `homelab.mdc` for the full documentation rule and README structure template.
